-% Given a Word and a set of Placed words, locates a candidate 
+% Letter-presence bitmask (experiment E-H8). One bit per distinct letter: the
+% bit index is the char code masked to 6 bits, so a-z (33..58), A-Z (1..26) and
+% 0-9 (48..57) each get a DISTINCT bit - no collisions on any real crossword
+% alphabet. The derived test is CONSERVATIVE: mask(A) /\ mask(B) =:= 0 PROVES A
+% and B share no letter (a shared letter is the same char, hence the same bit,
+% and always survives the AND). Two different chars whose codes coincide mod 64
+% would collide, producing only a FALSE POSITIVE (AND =\= 0 while disjoint),
+% which is safe wherever the mask is used here: find_intersecting_word/6 then
+% falls through to the exact intersection (which yields no candidate for a truly
+% disjoint pair anyway), and inc_count/10 merely recomputes an exact count it
+% could have carried forward. A false NEGATIVE never occurs, so the mrv_inc
+% no-under-count invariant is preserved unconditionally.
+letters_mask(Letters, Mask) :-
+    foldl(add_letter_bit, Letters, 0, Mask).
+
+add_letter_bit(Ch, In, Out) :-
+    char_code(Ch, Code),
+    Out is In \/ (1 << (Code /\ 63)).
+
+% Mask of an answer atom, TABLED on the atom: a pure function of the answer, so
+% each distinct answer is scanned once per process and every later read is an
+% O(1) table hit. Strips the same separators as entry_letters/2, so
+% answer_mask(A) equals letters_mask of A's placed letters exactly.
+:- table answer_mask/2.
+answer_mask(Answer, Mask) :-
+    atom_chars(Answer, Chars0),
+    exclude(mask_sep, Chars0, Chars),
+    letters_mask(Chars, Mask).
+
+mask_sep(' ').
+mask_sep('-').
+
+
+% Given a Word and a set of Placed words, locates a candidate
